# One-off Scripts — Usage & Cleanup Policy

## When a script is appropriate

Writing a one-off script to `scripts/` is acceptable when an MCP tool call is not practical:

- **Large payload**: The content to send is too large to inline safely as a tool argument (e.g. a full Confluence page body with tables, thousands of characters of HTML).
- **Multi-step atomic operation**: The task requires chaining API calls (e.g. GET current version → transform → PUT) that are safer and more transparent as a single executable file.
- **Bulk / batch operation**: The task touches many records (e.g. migrate 50 issues, update 20 pages) and a loop with logging is clearer than repeated tool calls.
- **Transformation + write**: The content requires non-trivial processing (parsing, reformatting, translating) before writing back to an external system.

## When a script is NOT appropriate

Do NOT write a script if a single MCP tool call can do the job cleanly. Prefer tools for:

- Reading data (always use tools)
- Simple single-record writes with small payloads
- Anything that fits comfortably in a tool argument

## Naming & placement

- Place all one-off scripts in `scripts/` with a descriptive name, e.g. `migrate-issues-to-new-project.mjs`.
- Use the `.mjs` extension (ES modules, consistent with the rest of the project).

## Cleanup — mandatory

One-off scripts are **temporary**. After the script has been run successfully:

1. Delete the script file immediately.
2. Do not commit it to git.

If the script may be reused, note it explicitly to the user; otherwise delete it.
